%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Material Exergy}
\label{sec:exergy_of_materials}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The exergy of a material ($B$) is the minimum amount of work
that could be extracted
by processes that take the material
to equilibrium with the reference environment,
defined by its temperature ($T_0$), pressure ($P_0$), and chemical composition.
Thus, the total exergy of a material ($B$)
is the sum of the work of two reversible processes
that bring the system
(a)~from $T$ and $P$ to
    $T_0$ and $P_0$
    (without changes in the chemical composition) and
(b)~from its chemical composition to
    to the reference chemical composition
    (while the system remains at $T_0$ and $P_0$).
Reference environments can include the atmosphere,
the ocean, or the Earth's crust.
Species in reference environments are characterized
by partial pressure ($P_i = P_0 y_i$) in the atmosphere,
by concentrations ($C_i$) in the ocean,
and by mole fraction ($y_i$)
in the Earth's crust.
We take reference environments
from \citet[Table~11.1-11.7]{Valero_2015}.\\

Natural resources have a positive material exergy ($b$) (in units of $kJ/mol$)
because they have a chemical composition
that differentiates them from their Environment.
Material exergy is comprised of four components:
physical exergy ($b_{ph}$),
chemical exergy ($b_{ch}$),
concentration exergy ($b_{c}$),
and comminution exergy ($b_{com}$).
Comminution exergy is minimal and ignored for a material conversion chain analysis
\citep[p.280]{Valero_2015}.
Here, we assume that the material is at
$T_0$ and $P_0$;
thus, physical exergy ($b_{ph}$) is zero.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Mixture ($m$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_mixtures}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
The total material exergy of a mixture ($B_m$) at a statepoint is

\begin{equation}\label{eq:specific_exergy_of_current_statepoint_definition}
   B_m = N_m b_m \; ,
 \end{equation}
%
where $B_m$ is in units of $kJ_m$,
$N_m$ is the amount of the mixture (in units of $mol_m$),
and $b_m$ is the molar intensive material exergy of the mixture (in units of $kJ_m/mol_m$).

The material exergy of a mixture may be account for each species with

\begin{equation}\label{eq:total_exergy_of_current_statepoint_mixture_definition}
   B_m = \sum_i{{N_i}{b_i}}
       = N_m\sum_i{{y_i}{b_i}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $N_i$ ($mol_i$) is the number of moles of a compound
$b_i$ is the molar intensive material exergy
of a compound ($kJ_i/mol_i$),
and $y_i$ is the mole fraction
of a compound in a mixture ($mol_i/mol_m$).

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Compound ($i$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_compounds}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Molar intensive material exergy ($b_i$) is defined as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:general_material_exergy_definition}
  b_i = b_{ch,i} + b_{c,i}
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is the chemical exergy of a compound (in units of $kJ_i/mol_i$)
and $b_{c,i}$ is the concentration exergy of a compound (in units of $kJ_i/mol_i$).
See \citet[p.276]{Valero_2015}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsubsection{Chemical exergy($b_{ch}$)}
\label{ssec:chemical_exergy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is the minimum work needed
to form that compound.

The chemical exergy of each compound is dependent on whether it exists
in the reference environment or not.
The reference environment for chemical exergy,
within a material conversion chain,
is standard temperature and pressure.

If the compound ($i$) does not exist
in the reference environment,
then the chemical exergy is the amount of work obtained
in the reversible chemical reactions
that decompose the pure compound
to the compound ($i$) in equilibrium
with the environment.

The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}
  b_{ch,i} = \Delta{G_{f,i}} + \sum_{i}{n_{j}b_{ch,j}}
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is in units of $kJ_i/mol_i$
and Gibbs energy of formation ($\Delta{G_f}$) is the minimum therymodynamic potential
of a species reaching chemical equilibrium (in units of $kJ_i/mol_i$).

$\Delta{G_{f}}$ values are taken from \citet{Dean_1979}
and \citet{Gibbs_formation}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsubsection{Concentration Exergy ($b_c$)}
\label{sssec:concentration_exergy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The concentration exergy of a compound ($b_{c,i}$) is the the minimum work required
to concentrate a species
from a pure substance to the molar concentration
at a statepoint.
The definition of concentration exergy is derived from the entropy of mixing.

The entropy of a mixture ($S_m$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:specific_entropy_of_mixture_definition}
  S_m = -RN_m(y_{1}\ln{y_{1}} + y_{2}\ln{y_{2}} + y_{3}\ln{y_{3}} + \ldots)
          = -RN_m\sum_{i} y_{i}\ln{y_{i}}
\end{equation}
%
where $S_m$ is in units of $kJ/mol_m~K$
and $R$ is the universal gas constant (in units of $kJ/mol_i~K$).

The molar fraction of a species always refers back to the species
as a pure substance.
The molar fraction of a pure substance ($y_{i,0}$) is equal to one
because the number of total moles in a mixture
is equivalent to the total moles of the species.\\

\citet{Valero_2015} define concentration exergy of a compound ($b_{c,i}$) as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy}
  b_{c,i} = -RT_0(\ln(y_i) - \ln(y_{i,0})) \; .
\end{equation}
%
Simplifying \ref{eq:concentration_exergy} with $y_i,0 = 1$ and $\ln(y_{i,0})$ gives

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy_definition}
  b_{c,i} = -RT_0(\ln(y_i))
\end{equation}
%
because the natural log of a pure substance's molar fraction is always zero.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsubsection{Elements ($j$)}
\label{sssec:elements}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
The chemical exergy of elements ($b_{ch,j}$) is standardized
based on the Crepuscular Earth Model
from \citet[Table~9.1]{Valero_2015}.

The moles of an element within a compound ($n_{j,i}$),
when multiplied by the chemical exergy of the element,
is added to the Gibbs free energy
in \ref{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}.

