\subsection{The exergy of energy}
\label{sec:exergy_of_energy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

A material conversion chain
uses both material and energy inputs.
To change a mixture's composition,
energy is used
to concentrate and remove components.

The exergy of energy is calculated by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X_i = \phi_i E_i \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\phi_i$ is the exergy to energy ratio and
$E_i$ is the energy of compound (in units of $kJ$),
e.g.\ natural gas.

The total exergy of energy
at any statepoint
in a material conversion chain
is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X = \sum_i \phi_i E_i \; .
\end{equation}
%
We obtain $\phi_i$ values from \citet{Kotas_1995}.
See Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix_phi}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Efficiency Methods}
\label{ssec:efficiency_methods}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Several efficiencies can be  calculated
for processes in a material conversion chain.
***Change figure***
\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{images/efficiency_methods.pdf}
  \caption{Three efficiency methods used for energy and material exergy conversion chains.}
  \label{fig:efficiencymethods}
\end{figure}

%
We suggest three methods for calculating efficiencies
based on exergy upgrades, focus on a product,
and focus on whole streams. (See Figure 2.)

\begin{itemize}
  \item The ***Bejan*** method expresses
  how much energy is necessary
  to concentrate a specific element or compound.
  We define ***Bejan*** efficiency as
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Bejan Efficiency}
  \eta_{Bejan} = \frac{N_i(b_{m,i,1} - b_{m,i,0})}{\sum{X_{in}}} \; .
  \end{equation}
  where $b_{m,i,1}$ is the exergy of a compound in a mixture at statepoint 1 (in units of $kJ_i/mol_i$).
  \item The ***Resource*** method focuses on the main product stream's exergy output
  compared to the total exergy input.
  The ***Resource*** efficiency is defined as
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Resource Efficiency}
  \eta_{Resource} = \frac{(B_{m,i,1})}{\sum{X_{in}}+\sum{B_{in}}} \; .
  \end{equation}

  The ***Resource*** method quantifies
  how efficiently a process
  can separate one material
  from waste streams.

  \item The ***Student*** method focuses on the total exergy output
  compared to the total exergy input.
  We define the ***Student*** efficiency as
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Student Efficiency}
  \eta_{Students} = \frac{\sum{B_{out}}}{\sum{X_{in}} + \sum{B_{in}}} \; .
  \end{equation}

  The ***Student*** method is helpful
  for quick efficiency calculations
  of an overall process.

\end{itemize}



