\subsection{PSUT Matrix Structure}
\label{ssec:psut_matrix}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The energy and material conversion chains are used
to understand how masses and energy are applied to processes.
The outputs of materials and energy end up
in specific sectors of the economy.
Physical Supply Use Table (PSUT) matrices
show which products, industries, and sectors
materials and energy interact with.

Benefits of the PSUT framework include quantification of product flows,
final demand for energy and material products tracked to primary resources,
and end-use efficiency for material, energy, and exergy.

The PSUT framework is applied to conversion chains.
Once the material and energy conversion chains are modeled,
both chains may be converted to exergy chains.

We apply the Physical Supply-Use Table (PSUT) framework
from \citet[Figure~1]{Aramendia_2022}
to material, energy, and exergy conversion chains developed in Section~\ref{sec:results}
below.
The PSUT framework comprises four matrices.
The resource matrix (\textbf{R}) contains exogeneous inputs to a conversion chain.
The use (\textbf{U}) and make (\textbf{V}) matrices
describe the consumption and production of materials and energy by processes in conversion chains.
The final demand matrix (\textbf{Y}) includes product consumption by economic sectors.
(See \citet[Table~1]{Aramendia_2022}.)

